To display a Q-Form on a Q-Fab-Action click event, you can use the `v-model` directive to bind a variable to the visibility of the Q-Form, and toggle that variable on the click event of the Q-Fab-Action. Here's an example of how to achieve this:

```html
<template>
  <div>
    <q-fab v-if="!showForm" icon="add" @click="openForm" />

    <q-form v-model="showForm" @hide="hideForm">
      <!-- Form fields go here -->

      <div class="q-mt-md">
        <q-btn label="Submit" color="primary" @click="submitForm" />
      </div>
    </q-form>
  </div>
</template>

<script>
export default {
  data() {
    return {
      showForm: false
    };
  },
  methods: {
    openForm() {
      this.showForm = true;
    },
    hideForm() {
      this.showForm = false;
    },
    submitForm() {
      // Handle form submission logic here
      this.showForm = false; // Hide the form after submission
    }
  }
};
</script>
```

In this example, initially, the Q-Fab-Action is displayed. On clicking it, the `openForm` method is called, which sets `showForm` to `true`, making the Q-Form visible. When the form is hidden (using the back button or other means), the `hideForm` method is called, which sets `showForm` back to `false`. The form can be submitted using the Q-Button, which triggers the `submitForm` method. After successful form submission, `showForm` is set back to `false` to hide the form.

Apologies for the confusion. If you want to display the Q-Form on a button click instead of the Q-Fab-Action, you can use the same concept as before. Here's an updated example:

```html
<template>
